A3.T7.caption: Table 7 :  Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) and Error Bound Accuracy (ACC) at  δ 𝛿 \delta  (scaled up by a factor of 100, mean over 9 trials) of latency prediction on the NAS-Bench-201 dataset. In each setting, the best performances are highlighted in  green .
references:
To measure the encoding quality of FlowerFormer in various aspects and validate its effectiveness, we conduct a latency prediction experiment on NAS-Bench-201, comparing FlowerFormer with NAR-Former [50].
For this comparison, we utilize Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) and Error Bound Accuracy (Acc(δ𝛿\delta)), the same metrics employed by Yi et al. [50] for latency prediction.
As shown in Table 7, FlowerFormer outperforms NAR-Former in the latency prediction task.

A3.T8.caption: Table 8 :  Linear Correlation (LC) and Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) (mean over 9 trials) on the NAS-Bench-101 dataset. In each setting, the best performances are highlighted in  green .
references:
To evaluate the superior performance of FlowerFormer across different evaluation criteria, we examine performance on NAS-Bench-101 using the Pearson Coefficient of Linear Correlation (LC) and Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE).
As shown in Table 8, FlowerFormer shows the best performance in all the settings.

A3.T9.caption: Table 9 :  Kendall’s Tau (scaled up by a factor of 100, mean over 9 trials) on the ENAS dataset. In each setting, the best performances are highlighted in  green .
references:
In this section, we analyze the performance of FlowerFormer on ENAS, an additional dataset consisting of two cells. As shown in Table 9, FlowerFormer achieves the second-best performance in the dataset.
We hypothesize that the sub-optimal performance of FlowerFormer stems from its failure to account for interactions between two cells. Although there is information flow between two cells, FlowerFormer lacks a dedicated global attention module that can capture their interactions.
This limitation suggests that enhancing the global attention module to incorporate strategies like cross-attention could be a valuable future research direction.
